Photo: James Nielsen, Staff Image 69 of 69 Monica, Ginuwine, Teddy Riley set for '90s Block Party 1 / 69 Back to Gallery Smart Financial Centre at Sugar Land is gonna take you back.
The H-Town '90s Block Party is set for May 6 at the newly opened venue. Heading up the cast of perfomers is Guy feat Teddy Riley, credited with creating the New Jack Swing sound.
Also on the lineup are R&B songbird Monica, ab-flashing heartthrob Ginuwine and groups 112 and Next.
Tickets are $64.50-$94.50 and go on sale at 10 a.m. Friday via Ticketmaster
Guy's hits included "I Like", "My Fantasy," "Do Me Right" and "Teddy's Jam." Riley went on to become an in-demand producer and songwriter.
Monica was one of the '90s most consistent hitmakers. She scored a whopping nine consecutive top 10 pop singles: "Don't Take It Personal (Just One of Dem Days)," "Like This and Like That," "Before You Walk Out of My Life," "Why I Love You So Much," "Ain't Nobody," "For You I Will," "The Boy is Mine" with Brandy," "The First Night" and "Angel of Mine."
HERE'S YOUR CHANCE: Grammy-winning rapper comes to town
"So Gone" a top 10 pop and No. 1 R&B hit in 2003, was resurrected last year thanks to Chance the Rapper, who freestyled several lines over the song's instrumental and posted it to Twitter. It was retweeted by Monica and Elliott, who encouraged fans to create their own rap for the #SoGoneChallenge.
Ginuwine's biggest hit, of course, was 1996 debut single "Pony." He went on to score several more hits, including "So Anxious," "Differences" and "In Those Jeans."
Quartet 112's most successful singles included "It's Over Now" and "Peaches & Cream." Next scored a No. 1 smash with 1998's "Too Close."
